"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872439","Department for Education","false","2018-03-29","<p>Under the new annual net earned income threshold of £15,400, it is estimated that by 2023 around 7,000 more children will benefit from the two-year-old entitlement compared to the previous benefits system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872439/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-29T16:40:07.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872439/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872439/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-26","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 26 March 2018 to Question 133554, on children: day care, what estimate he has made of the number of 2-year-olds who will be eligible in 2023.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","134345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872440","Home Office","false","2018-04-11","<p>The latest data made available to the Home Office is for the period July 2015 to March 2017 where 56 Orders were issued in total, consisting of 37 Prevention Orders on conviction, and 19 Risk Orders on application. These figures were published in the 2017 UK annual report on Modern Slavery;</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/652366/2017_uk_annual_report_on_modern_slavery.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/652366/2017_uk_annual_report_on_modern_slavery.pdf</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872440/answer","2017_uk_annual_report_on_modern_slavery.pdf","2017_uk_annual_report_on_modern_slavery.pdf","2017 UK Annual report on modern slavery","2017 UK Annual report on modern slavery",,"2018-04-11T15:49:16.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872440/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872440/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-26","Slavery: Court Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many Slavery and Trafficking Prevention and Risk Orders have been granted (1) on application, and (2) on sentencing.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL6627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872441","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Government consulted on the effectiveness of the code in assuring acceptable management practices and standards as part of our consultation on extending mandatory licensing of HMOs. We acknowledged as part of our response, that a significant number of consultees were satisfied with the code as being a means of ensuring acceptable management practices and standards in student accommodation. However, membership of a code alone does not guarantee that the student accommodation meets local standards set by a local authority and therefore should not necessarily provide an exemption from HMO licensing.</p><p>Educational establishments have a duty of care defined by statutory obligations, for example through the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, that they must fulfil, both in the provision of education and accommodation to its students. They are also subject to regulation by an independent regulator, the Office for Students. However, private companies are not subject to the same levels of regulation and therefore should not be exempted from House in Multiple Occupation licensing.</p><p>Therefore, the Government does not have plans to remove requirements for private providers of purpose-built student accommodation who are part of an approved national code to be subject to houses in multiple occupation licensing.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872441/answer",,,,,"HL6629 ; HL6630 ; HL6632","2018-04-03T14:20:13.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872441/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872441/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-26","Housing: Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the cost to providers of purpose-built student accommodation of being required to pay for house in multiple occupation licences.","false","Biography information for Lord Flight",,"Lord Flight","HL6628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872442","Department for Education","false","2018-03-29","<p>We are in the final stages of a procurement process to better equip the schools workforce to support pupils with all types of Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND). We expect to award the contract in April and will announce the contractor at that point.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872442/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-29T16:42:43.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872442/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872442/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-26","Department for Education: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 26 March 2018 to Question 133561, what organisation or organisations received the contract related to a new SEND school workforce contract, the procurement for which began in December 2017.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","134346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872443","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Government consulted on the effectiveness of the code in assuring acceptable management practices and standards as part of our consultation on extending mandatory licensing of HMOs. We acknowledged as part of our response, that a significant number of consultees were satisfied with the code as being a means of ensuring acceptable management practices and standards in student accommodation. However, membership of a code alone does not guarantee that the student accommodation meets local standards set by a local authority and therefore should not necessarily provide an exemption from HMO licensing.</p><p>Educational establishments have a duty of care defined by statutory obligations, for example through the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, that they must fulfil, both in the provision of education and accommodation to its students. They are also subject to regulation by an independent regulator, the Office for Students. However, private companies are not subject to the same levels of regulation and therefore should not be exempted from House in Multiple Occupation licensing.</p><p>Therefore, the Government does not have plans to remove requirements for private providers of purpose-built student accommodation who are part of an approved national code to be subject to houses in multiple occupation licensing.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872443/answer",,,,,"HL6628 ; HL6630 ; HL6632","2018-04-03T14:20:13.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872443/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872443/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-26","Housing: Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of